The problem and (sub-optimal) solutions¶

Default colors in matplotlib¶

Plotting stuff inside a loop with random colors ends up repeating the same colors...

The default python palette for color selection (the one used when you do not specify a given color) is the 10 first colors in the category10 colormap:

So, if we plot lines in a loop, we get:

In [2]:
def plot_lines(N,colors=[None]):
    x = np.linspace(0,10,100)
    for i in range(N):
        y = x*i + 0
        if colors[0] == None:
            plt.plot(x,y,label='Iteration '+str(i),lw=2)
        else:
            plt.plot(x,y,label='Iteration '+str(i),c=colors[i],lw=2)
    plt.legend(fontsize=10)
In [3]:
plot_lines(13)

A tedious solution (#1)¶

You can choose your color cycle by directly specifiying the colors you want:

In [4]:
from cycler import cycler
import matplotlib as mpl
mpl.rcParams['axes.prop_cycle'] = cycler(color='bgrcmyk') # bLUE, gREEN, rED, cYAN, mAGENTA, yELLOW, BLACk
In [5]:
plot_lines(13)

Or define it from a set of color names from the matplotlib list of colors:

In [6]:
# Or a list of colors:
mpl.rcParams['axes.prop_cycle'] = cycler('color', ['blue', 'red', 'orange', 'pink', 'green', 'dodgerblue', 'darkmagenta', 'peru', 'salmon', 'purple','tomato','coral','gold','aqua'])
In [7]:
plot_lines(13)

ok... but:

  • The color selection is not optimal (some colors may look similar)
  • You have to manually select them
  • Depending on the problem you will need to add more colors
  • They might contain colors that look the same for color-blind people

A simple (but not optimal) solution¶

You can always use the matplotlib colormaps as selectors if you have many lines (or markers) to plot:

In [8]:
cmap = mpl.colormaps['plasma']
N=13
# Take colors at regular intervals spanning the colormap.
colors = cmap(np.linspace(0, 1, N))
x = np.linspace(0,10,100)
for i in range(N):
    y = x*i + 0 
    plt.plot(x,y,label='Iteration '+str(i), color=colors[i])

Matplotlib colormaps are numerous, some few examples:

Still...:

  • Colormaps are very sequential (although other options are available)
  • Still difficult for color-blind people depending on the colormap chosen
  • Poor control on the exact colors and on how distinguishable are among them

The nice solution: distinctipy¶

What is distinctipy for?¶

In [9]:
import distinctipy
  • Pseudo-random generator of colors to maximize their color-wise distance
  • Control on the type of colors
  • Takes color-blindness into account (if you wish)
  • Can use pastel-style colors
  • Generates any number of colors you want that look inherently different

Generate N distinct colours¶

In [10]:
# Generate 16 distinct colours (excluding black and white by default)
colors = distinctipy.get_colors(16)
# display the colours
distinctipy.color_swatch(colors)

Note: This will create a different palette each time you run it. If you wat to keep always the same remember to fix the seed using the rng parameter.

In [11]:
# Generate 16 distinct colours (excluding black and white by default)
colors = distinctipy.get_colors(16,rng=999)
distinctipy.color_swatch(colors)
In [12]:
# You can create as many as you need:
colors = distinctipy.get_colors(10)
plot_lines(10,colors=colors)

You can even add a pastel factor to make colors even prettier:

In [13]:
# You can create as many as you need:
colors = distinctipy.get_colors(10,pastel_factor=0.5)
plot_lines(10,colors=colors)

Add N additional colors¶

If you have already used a given set of colors (e.g.: red, gree, blue, white, black) and need to add a new color critically different from them:

In [14]:
input_colors = ['orange', 'green', 'yellow']
for ii,i in enumerate(input_colors):
    Npoints = 100
    for j in range(Npoints):
        x,y = np.random.normal(ii,0.5), np.random.normal(ii,0.5)
        plt.plot(x,y,'o',c=i)
In [15]:
rgb_input_colors = [mpl.colors.to_rgb(i) for i in input_colors]
new_colors = distinctipy.get_colors(3, rgb_input_colors)
output_colors = rgb_input_colors+ new_colors
In [16]:
for ii,i in enumerate(output_colors):
    Npoints = 100
    for j in range(Npoints):
        x,y = np.random.normal(ii,0.5), np.random.normal(ii,0.5)
        plt.plot(x,y,'o',c=i)

Another example: you love the tomato color and need 2 others to plot three Gaussians:

In [17]:
input_colors = ['tomato']
rgb_input_colors = [mpl.colors.to_rgb(i) for i in input_colors]
new_colors = distinctipy.get_colors(2, rgb_input_colors,pastel_factor=0.8)
output_colors = rgb_input_colors+ new_colors
from scipy.stats import norm

x = np.linspace(0,10,1000)
for mu,sig,color in zip([5,6,2],[2,0.5,3],output_colors):
    plt.plot(x,norm.pdf(x,loc=mu,scale=sig),c=color)
    plt.fill_between(x,x*0,norm.pdf(x,loc=mu,scale=sig),facecolor=color,alpha=0.3)

Text within color¶

You can also use distinctipy to choose whether to use black or white for text on top of a given color to maximize the contrast:

In [22]:
# generate 16 distinct colours
colors = distinctipy.get_colors(16)

# pick black or white text for each colour
text = [distinctipy.get_text_color(color) for color in colors]

# display main colours, inverted colours and text
distinctipy.color_swatch(colors, show_text=True)

and generate the completely opposite color to a given color:

In [23]:
# generate a colour as distinct as possible from each colour in colors
inverted = distinctipy.invert_colors(colors)
In [24]:
distinctipy.color_swatch(colors, edgecolors=inverted)

Colors for different types of colourblindness¶

There are many types of coloblindness:

  • Normal: Normal vision
  • Protanopia: Red-green colorblindness (1% males)
  • Protanomaly: Red-green colorblindness (1% males, 0.01% females)
  • Deuteranopia: Red-green colorblindness (1% males)
  • Deuteranomaly: Red-green colorblindness (most common type: 6% males, 0.4% females)
  • Tritanopia: Blue-yellow colourblindness (<1% males and females)
  • Tritanomaly: Blue-yellow colourblindness (0.01% males and females)
  • Achromatopsia: Total colourblindness
  • Achromatomaly: Total colourblindness

What happens to color-blind people when we do not take them into account?

In [46]:
from distinctipy import colorblind
from distinctipy import examples
colorblind_type = "Deuteranomaly"
dataset = "s3"

print("Colours distinct for normal vision:")
colorblind.simulate_clusters(
    dataset=dataset, 
    colorblind_type=colorblind_type, 
    colorblind_distinct=False
)

Colours distinct for normal vision:
In [48]:
print("Colours distinct for " + colorblind_type + " colourblindness:")
colorblind.simulate_clusters(
    dataset=dataset, 
    colorblind_type=colorblind_type, 
    colorblind_distinct=True
)

Colours distinct for Deuteranomaly colourblindness:

In practice, if you want to draw lines taking a particular type of colorblindness:

In [49]:
colors = distinctipy.get_colors(10,colorblind_type='Deuteranomaly')
#colors = distinctipy.get_colors(10,colorblind_type='Achromatopsia')
plot_lines(10,colors=colors)

You can also check how a colorblind person would see your plot:

In [50]:
with_cb = [distinctipy.colorblind.colorblind_filter(c,colorblind_type='Deuteranomaly') for c in colors]
plot_lines(10,colors=with_cb)
